  "texts": [
    "The SEM image in Fig. 7 depicts the effect of RHA on the concrete microstructure.",
    "Review Discover Civil Engineering (2024) 1:145 | https://doi.org/10.1007/s44290-024-00154-z Moghadam et al. [66] observed that while the structure of calcium silicate hydrate (C-S-H) remains largely unchanged, GGBFS increases chloride binding capacity by 15-20% without significantly affecting sulfate resistance, thereby improving the concrete's resistance to chloride ingress.",
    "Zou et al. [67] found that GGBFS, at various replacement levels, enhances durability by improving chloride binding and reducing sulfate content, despite minimal changes to the C-S-H structure.",
    "Chi et al. [68] highlighted that GGBFS increases concrete density and reduces pore connectivity by 15-25%, which minimizes pathways for aggressive ions and moisture, thus enhancing microstructural stability.",
    "Additionally, Cleetus et al. [69] and Cahyani and Rusdianto [70] reported that higher GGBFS levels (up to 40%) lead to a 20-25% increase in microstructural density Fig."
  ]
